{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537292"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:15:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:15:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16019"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16019","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16019"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.9,0.02,0.05,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8710"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63538"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8710"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16019"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48992"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1374"},{"type":"tags","id":"4447"},{"type":"tags","id":"4479"},{"type":"tags","id":"4480"},{"type":"tags","id":"12806"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20839"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63538"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman has just given birth to her first child via vacuum-assisted delivery following a prolonged second stage of labour. The baby weighs 3.4 kg and has Apgar scores of 8 and 9 at one and five minutes. The mother plans to exclusively breastfeed. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination of the newborn, there is moderate moulding of the head with a small cephalhaematoma noted at the site of vacuum application.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most appropriate to reduce the risk of haemorrhagic complications in this newborn?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hepatitis B vaccine","Vitamin K","Fresh frozen plasma","Tranexamic acid","Platelets"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis newborn requires vitamin K prophylaxis to prevent vitamin K deficiency bleeding (VKDB). The risk is particularly relevant given the vacuum-assisted delivery and presence of a cephalhaematoma, which increase the risk of bleeding complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin K\u003C/strong\u003E is essential for the production of clotting factors II, VII, IX, and X. Newborns are deficient in vitamin K due to poor placental transfer, low stores at birth, and minimal content in breast milk. A single intramuscular dose at birth effectively prevents both early and late VKDB.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis B vaccine\u003C/strong\u003E is important for all newborns but does not affect coagulation or prevent bleeding complications. It should be given within 24 hours of birth but is unrelated to the management of potential bleeding risks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFresh frozen plasma\u003C/strong\u003E would only be indicated if there was active bleeding or severe coagulopathy, which is not present in this case. It is not used prophylactically in otherwise healthy newborns.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranexamic acid\u003C/strong\u003E is an antifibrinolytic agent that would not be appropriate for routine prophylaxis in a healthy newborn. It is used in specific situations of active bleeding or high bleeding risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlatelets\u003C/strong\u003E would only be indicated if there was thrombocytopenia or platelet dysfunction, which is not suggested in this case. Routine platelet administration is not appropriate for healthy newborns.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vitamin K prophylaxis should be given to all newborns within the first few hours of life to prevent vitamin K deficiency bleeding.","Instrumental delivery with associated birth trauma increases the risk of vitamin K deficiency bleeding.","Hepatitis B vaccination should be given to all newborns within 24 hours of birth, independent of delivery method."],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RANZCOG). Vitamin K administration to newborn infants to prevent vitamin K deficiency bleeding in infancy [Internet]. East Melbourne: RANZCOG; 2022. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/2022/05/Vitamin-K-Administration-to-Newborn-Infants-to-Prevent-Vitamin-K-Deficiency-Bleeding-in-Infancy.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48992"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16019"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48992","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48992"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-21T14:07:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T14:08:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8710"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63538"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"crea